Did you know that Dick Cheney and Kamala Harris were both presidents? Well, technically they were acting presidents. An acting president is someone who carries out the powers and duties of the American president even though that person actually doesn't hold the office. And both Cheney and Harris did this because the Constitution says that the Vice President is first in line to serve as acting president. For 85 minutes on November 19, 2021, Harris became the first woman with presidential power when President Joe Biden was under anesthesia for a colonoscopy. Cheney was acting president twice, also during colonoscopies. On both June 29, 2002 and July 21, 2008, Cheney served as acting president when President George W. Bush was also under anesthesia for colonoscopies. The only other time in American history when a vice president served as acting president was when George H.W. Bush filled in for President Ronald Reagan when he had colon cancer surgery on July 13, 1985.

Welcome to Queer History 101 Part 3. We all know the rainbow flag as the symbol of the LGBTQ plus community. But why? The rainbow flag was created in 1978 by artist, veteran and drag performer Gilbert Baker. He was commissioned to create a flag for San Diego's Pride Parade by another gay icon, politician Harvey Milk. The different colours within the flag are intended to represent togetherness since LGBTQ plus people come in all races, ages and genders, and rainbows are both natural and beautiful. The original flag featured eight colours, each having a different meaning. Hot pink for sex, red for life, orange for healing, yellow for sunlight, green for nature, turquoise for art, indigo for harmony, violet for spirit. Some flags added black and brown stripes to honour black and brown members of the community. A recent update is the progress flag, which features the chevron to the side of the original flag to honor trans as well as black and brown community members.

The world of eagles is incredibly diverse, with over 60 different species spread across the globe. Each species of eagle has adapted to its specific environment, showcasing unique characteristics and behaviors. The bald eagle, with its iconic white head, reigns in North America, symbolizing strength and freedom. In South America, the harpy eagle, one of the largest and most powerful, reigns supreme in the rainforest canopy. The golden eagle, found in the northern hemisphere, is admired for its striking golden-brown plumage and impressive hunting skills. Each species differs in size, habitat, diet, and hunting strategies, but all share common traits of strength, agility, and majesty. The diversity of eagle species is a testament to the adaptability and resilience of these birds, making them a fascinating subject for ornithologists and bird enthusiasts alike.
